TI  - LMACV: A lightweight multiscale ACmix-VMamba framework for efficient multimodal medical image fusion
T2  - NEUROCOMPUTING
LA  - English
KW  - Image fusion
KW  - Medical image
KW  - VMamba
KW  - ACmix
KW  - Deep learning
KW  - NETWORK
KW  - PERFORMANCE
KW  - TRANSFORM
AB  - Current imaging sensors are incapable of simultaneously obtaining functional metabolic activity and structural tissue features, thus substantially limiting diagnostic accuracy in clinical practice. Multimodal Medical Image Fusion (MMIF) uses complementary data from MRI, CT, PET, and SPECT to improve diagnostic representations and promote precise tissue segmentation. Recent developments in deep learning, particularly Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs) and transformer models, have greatly improved the performance and flexibility of image fusion methods. Existing models, however, have two significant drawbacks. CNNs face the problem of long-range context due to the limitations of their small receptive fields. Conversely, transformers are ideal for capturing global dependencies but have a quadratic computational overhead, limiting their scalability. In this study, we present LMACV, a lightweight fusion framework that integrates grouped ACmix for local details and a Multi-Stage Visual State Space (MVSS) module-built upon VMamba-for efficient global modeling within a two-level multiscale pyramid. The design increases receptive field and representation hierarchy while maintaining linear complexity and low parameter counts. Experiments on medical image fusion tasks show that LMACV outperforms previous approaches in visual quality and quantitative parameters. Furthermore, LMACV exhibits better generalization in downstream segmentation and detection tasks.
